 complex and morally controversial medical dilemmas aside from abortion and euthanasia. However, these quandaries are not unsolvable. This book proposes compensating organ donors within a publicly controlled monopsony. This proposal is quite similar to current practice in Spain, where compensation for cadaveric donation now occurs "in secret," as this text reveals. To build their recommendations, the authors provide a medical history of transplantation, a history of the development of national laws and waiting lists, a careful examination of the social costs and benefits of transplantation, a discussion of the causes of organ shortages, an evaluation of "partial" reforms tried or proposed, an extensive ethical evaluation of the current system and its competitors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDonation of organs, tissues, etcxEconomic aspects. 0aDonation of organs, tissues, etcxGovernment policy. 0aProcurement of organs, tissues, etcxEconomic aspects. 0aProcurement of organs, tissues, etcxGovernment policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aKaserman, David L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOsterkamp, Rigmar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804784641zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784641.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles